\includegraphics[scale=0.35]{Fig3}
\caption{(Color online)  The relative entropy coherence, \textit{$l_1$} norm coherence and entanglement as  functions of the initial state parameter $\theta$ and acceleration parameter $q$. The effective coupling parameter $\nu$ is fixed as $ \nu=0.05\pi$.}\label{Fig3}
\end{figure}
\begin{figure}[ht]
\includegraphics[scale=0.6]{Fig4}
\caption{(Color online)  Quantum coherence and entanglement as  functions of the initial state parameter $\theta$ and effective coupling parameter $\nu$ for an extremely large acceleration  ($q\rightarrow0.999$).}\label{Fig4}
\end{figure}

We also find that the  \textit{$l_1$} norm  coherence always equals to the relative entropy
coherence (REC) when the initial state parameter is $\theta=\pi/4$, which means that the  \textit{$l_1$} norm, the T-norm and relative entropy measurement of coherence are consistent in this case. However, they decease in different way for a non-maximum-coherence initial state.
We wonder that whether or not the consistency among these measurements is a general property of coherence. Therefore, in Fig. (\ref{Fig2}) we plot the REC and \textit{$l_1$} norm coherence for different initial state parameters with fixed coupling and acceleration parameters $q=0.5, \nu=0.05\pi$. We can see that the
value of different measurement of quantum  coherence
depends on the state parameter $\theta$ sensitively, which shows that the preparation of Alice and Rob's initial state has a non-trivial  influence on the consistency of quantum coherence. Note that \textit{$l_1$} norm  coherence  equals to REC only for incoherence case $\theta=0, \pi/2$ or maximum-coherence case $\theta=\pi/4$, we come to the conclusion that the measurement of coherence are not consistent  in a general case.


In Fig. (\ref{Fig3}), we plot the REC, \textit{$l_1$} norm coherence and entanglement versus  the initial state parameter $\theta$ and acceleration parameter $q$ for fixed $ \nu=0.05\pi$.  It is shown that both coherence and entanglement appear periodic behaviours for different $\theta$.
We should notice that as the increases of $\theta$,
the REC and \textit{$l_1$} norm coherence increase much more rapidly than that of quantum entanglement. In other words, the dynamic of quantum coherence is much more sensitive to the preparation of the detectors' initial state. In comparison with entanglement,
 quantum coherence is a better indicator for useful quantum resources in the accelerated system.

We have obtained  that only in the limit of infinite acceleration
$r\rightarrow \infty$ the quantum coherence goes to zero and the quantum entanglement of the same state decrease quite different over $q$.
To investigate this
further, we plot in Fig. (\ref{Fig4}) the coherence (\textit{$l_1$} norm) and entanglement as  functions of the initial state parameter $\theta$ and  coupling parameter $\nu$ for an extremely large acceleration  ($q\rightarrow0.999$). As discussed in
\cite{Schuller-Mann}, this limit describes a physical  picture that Alice is
freely falling into a black hole while the accelerated Rob
barely escapes from the black hole with an extremely large acceleration.
From Fig. (\ref{Fig4})  we can see that the coherence decreases more quickly than entanglement with the increasing of the effective coupling parameter $\nu$. That is to say, unlike the behavior of quantum coherence versus $q$, the quantum coherence is much more sensitive than entanglement to the coupling parameter.


\section{Conclusions}

In conclusion,  we have studied quantum coherence for two entangled Unruh-Dewitt detectors when one of them is accelerated and interacted with a massless scalar field.  We employ the Unruh-Dewitt detector model, which interacts locally with the neighbor external field. This model avoids from a physically unfeasible detection of global free models in the full space \cite{Landulfo,Landulfo1,tianwang,wangtian}. We find that the quantum coherence can not be frozen during the whole evolution, which is due to the influence of the Unruh thermal noise. It is shown that  quantum coherence is more robust than entanglement over thermal noise induced by Unruh effect and therefore the coherence type quantum resources are more accessible for relativistic quantum information processing tasks.  Note that \textit{$l_1$} norm  coherence  equals to REC only for some special cases, for example $\theta=0, \pi/2$ or $\theta=\pi/4$, which indicates that the measurement of coherence are not consistent in a relativistic setting. We also find that the dynamic of quantum coherence is much more sensitive than entanglement to the initial state parameter $\theta$ and the coupling parameter $\nu$. However, it is less sensitive than entanglement to the acceleration parameter $q$. The results of this paper, based on the equivalence principle, can be also applied to study the dynamic behavior of quantum coherence under the influence of Hawking radiation of black holes \cite{hujhep}.


